			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="995">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Thanks to Krista Bremer for her essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/4093">My Accidental Jihad</a>&rdquo; [October 2007], about her marriage to a Muslim man. I imagine it took courage to write. Bremer&rsquo;s experience illustrates the struggle for tolerance in an intolerant world, and I felt inspired in my own attempts to understand different cultures and religions.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Sarah Myers<br>Red Feather Lakes, Colorado</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="996">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Krista Bremer serves up her marriage with humor and spice, leavened with unblinking honesty. She and her husband, Ismail, clearly treat each other with kindness and respect, even when they do not entirely understand one another. Marriage has always seemed impossible to me, and this coupling of East and West proves that it is indeed possible, perhaps even desirable.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Tenley Newton<br>Cardiff, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="997">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Krista Bremer&rsquo;s essay about being married to a Libyan Muslim shows ignorance, racism, and intolerance. Her knowledge about Libya and Islam comes only through her husband and her brief trips to Libya. She reminds me of other European and American women I know who have married Libyans and want their husbands to adapt to their Western moral values, as if their culture and religion were far superior to their spouses&rsquo;.</p>

<p>It seems Bremer enjoys making fun of her husband&rsquo;s religion. She needs to learn Arabic and live in an Arabic country for a few years to understand Islamic culture. Really, she should have married someone of her own race and religion, but then she wouldn&rsquo;t be able to write essays like this one.</p>

<p>Oh, and regarding kissing: permissible during Ramadan.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Tariq Bukres<br>Portland, Oregon</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence-respond fill-pattern-light" id="998">
								<p><a href="/contributors/krista-bremer"><strong>Krista Bremer</strong></a> responds:</p>
							<p>My intent was not to make fun of my husband&rsquo;s religion; rather, I was trying to make fun of my own limitations in order to highlight his integrity. Ismail is my biggest fan &mdash; and at times my harshest critic. He is the first to read anything I write, and I would never publish anything he felt was disrespectful. When he read this piece, he laughed out loud.</p>

<p>If I&rsquo;d married someone just like me, I wouldn&rsquo;t have a six-year-old daughter who proudly teaches her classmates about her Libyan heritage, or a two-year-old son who exclaims, &ldquo;Allah!&rdquo; each time he sees the moon.</p>
	</div>


					</div>

